Introduction to Stream API in Java

Stream API was introduced in Java 8 to process collections in a functional and declarative way.

👉 It allows operations like:

filtering
mapping
sorting
collecting data

with cleaner and shorter code.

What is a Stream?

A Stream is a sequence of elements that supports operations on data.

👉 Important:

stream does NOT store data
it processes data from collections, arrays, etc.
Creating a Stream
From List
List<String> list = List.of("Apple", "Banana", "Orange");

Stream<String> stream = list.stream();
Basic Stream Example
list.stream()
    .filter(x -> x.startsWith("A"))
    .forEach(System.out::println);

👉 Output:

Apple
Stream Pipeline

A stream usually has 3 parts:

source → intermediate operations → terminal operation
1. Source

Where data comes from:

list.stream()
2. Intermediate Operations

They transform the stream.

Examples:

filter()
map()
sorted()

👉 They are lazy (do nothing until terminal operation)

3. Terminal Operation

Produces final result.

Examples:

forEach()
collect()
count()
Example Pipeline
list.stream()
    .filter(x -> x.length() > 5)
    .map(String::toUpperCase)
    .forEach(System.out::println);
Common Stream Methods
Method	Purpose
filter()	select elements
map()	transform elements
sorted()	sort elements
distinct()	remove duplicates
limit()	limit elements
collect()	collect result
Stream Does NOT Change Collection
list.stream().filter(x -> x.startsWith("A"));

👉 Original list stays unchanged

Why use Streams?
less boilerplate code
more readable
functional programming style
easier collection processing
Stream vs Loop
Traditional loop
for (String s : list) {
    if (s.startsWith("A")) {
        System.out.println(s);
    }
}
Stream version
list.stream()
    .filter(s -> s.startsWith("A"))
    .forEach(System.out::println);
Important Notes
streams are usually used once
streams are lazy
terminal operation starts execution
Summary
Stream API processes data from collections
supports functional-style programming
consists of:
source
intermediate operations
terminal operation
makes code cleaner and more expressive
